Just a few admin things around SR's from William Â this is a refresher of the process so please read through it and let's update our SR's accordingly.

As you are aware via previous email communication, when you pick up an SR in your team and you think it belongs to another team, the **person who picked up the SR** is **responsible** for **assigning** it to the **new team**. It should not go back to Support first to be re-assigned. There are multiple reasons for this arrangement.Â 

What is important in this process, is to **supply a reason** why you assign it to the next team. It is understandable that to supply a reason when you open the ticket and realize: "wrong team", is unnecessary. Sometimes the lines are not so clear-cut though. In these instances, it would help the next in line to understand why it is not in your team's domain, but theirs. It just cuts down ping-pong time and gives a better understanding of the mechanics of this beast that we are maintaining.

So please:

1. The dev re-assigns directly to the relevant team.
2. Where lines are blurred and issues are complex, please supply a bit of **context** to the next in line why you passed it on.

![image](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

When a ticket is re-assigned to your team without the needed **attachments and files**, I have asked them to respond to the email notification they will get and act ASAP to supply the **needed info**. If it is not supplied within a reasonable time period, you may then assign it back to the reporter to supply the needed info. Don't do it within 1 minute of it being re-assigned to your team.Â 

Obviously Urgent/High Priority SR's require a quicker response and asking via Teams will work.

The reason why I am bringing this up, is the **turn-around** times we have on SR's. Currently our average number of days for an SR = **65**, and the average number of days **between updates** = **6**. Which means SR's get touched once a week on average (not necessarily worked on). Devs only work dedicated on SR's 1 day per week (excluding urgent/high). So we need to make that 1 day as effective and productive as possible. It is better to solve a few SR's on the single day, than to chase around many SR's and none get solved.
